# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sportsman-s-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sportsman-s-park/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1881-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1881 throughout the world.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1881-in-baseball] Inter-league playoff: New York Mets (ECA) defeat Chicago (NL), 2 games to 1.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's second season in St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri and its second season in the American Association.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1883-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 65–33 during the season and finished second in the American Association.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's third season in St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and its third season in the American Association.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 67–40 during the season and finished fourth in the American Association.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons** baseball team finished with a 94–19 record and won the championship of the new Union Association (UA).
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] After the season, the UA folded and the Maroons joined the National League; they were the only UA team to continue past the 1884 season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] To this day, the Maroons' .832 winning percentage hasn't been matched by a professional baseball team.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons are not usually mentioned in the conversation of baseball teams with the best single-season records of all time.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] This team also set the record for the best start to a season in baseball history, going 20–0 before losing 8–1 to the Boston Reds on May 24, in their 21st game of the season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] The Maroons scored 887 runs while allowing 429, for a run differential of +458, the best in major-league history, as records and statistics of the UA are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:sportsman-s-park/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] The team was back in the news in 2015, when the Golden State Warriors started the 2015–16 season with an NBA-record 24 straight wins; this surpassed the Maroons' 20–0 start, which was previously the record for the four major professional sports leagues in the United States.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Sportsman's Park was the home field of both the St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis Browns of the American League, and the St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis Cardinals of the National League from 1920 to 1953, when the Browns relocated to Baltimore and were rebranded as the Orioles and the ballpark was renamed **Busch Stadium** (but still commonly called Sportsman's Park).
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The physical street address was 2911 North Grand Boulevard.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The ballpark was also the home to professional football: in 1923, it hosted St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis' first NFL team, the All-Stars, and later hosted the St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis Cardinals of the National Football League from 1960 (following the team's relocation from Chicago) until 1965, with Busch Memorial Stadium opening its doors in 1966.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Baseball was played on the Sportsman's Park site as early as 1867.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The tract was acquired in 1866 by August Solari, who began staging games there the following year.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis Brown Stockings in the National Association and the National League from 1875 to 1877.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] It was originally called the **Grand Avenue Ball Grounds**: some sources say the field was renamed **Sportsman's Park** in 1876, although local papers were not using that name until 1881, and some local papers used the alternate name "**Grand Avenue Park**" until at least 1885.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The first grandstand, one of three on the site, was built in 1881.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] At that time, the diamond and the grandstands were on the southeast corner of the block, for the convenience of fans arriving from Grand Avenue.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The park was leased by the then-major American Association entry, the St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The Browns were a very strong team in the mid-1880s, but their success waned.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] When the National League absorbed the strongest of the old Association teams in 1892, the Browns were brought along.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Soon they went looking for a new ballpark, finding a site just a few blocks northwest of the old one, and calling it **New Sportsman's Park**, which was later renamed Robison Field.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] They also changed team colors from Brown to Cardinal Red, thus acquiring a new nickname, and leaving their previous team colors as well as the old ballpark site available.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] After a fire at the Cardinals' ballpark on May 4, 1901, the club arranged to play some games at the original Sportsman's Park, which by then was being called "Athletic Park" and had only minimal seating.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] After a May 5 game, it was clear that the old park would no longer be a workable option: the team played on the road for a month while their own park was being rebuilt.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] When the American League Milwaukee Brewers moved to St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis in 1902 and took the Browns name, they built a new version of Sportsman's Park.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] They initially placed the diamond and the main stand at the northwest corner of the block.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] This Sportsman's Park saw football history made: it became both the practice field and home field for Saint Louis University football teams, coached by the visionary Eddie Cochems, father of the forward pass.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Although the first legal forward pass was thrown by Saint Louis' Bradbury Robinson in a road game at Carroll College in September 1906, Sportsman's Park was the scene of memorable displays of what Cochems called his "air attack" that season.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] These included a 39–0 thrashing of Iowa before a crowd of 12,000 and a 34–2 trouncing of Kansas witnessed by some 7,000.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Robinson launched an amazingly long pass in the game against the Jayhawks, which was variously reported to have traveled 48, 67 or 87 yards in the air.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] College Football Hall of Fame coach David M.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Nelson called the pass extraordinary, "considering the size, shape and weight" of the fat, rugby-style ball used at that time.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Sports historian John Sayle Watterson agreed.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] In his book, *College Football: History, Spectacle, Controversy*, Watterson described Robinson's long pass as "truly a breathtaking achievement".
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis finished with an 11–0 record in 1906, outscoring its opponents 407–11.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] In 1909, the Browns moved the diamond to its final location, at the southwest corner, in the shadow of a new steel and concrete grandstand, the third such stadium in the major leagues, and the second in the American League (after Shibe Park).
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The previous wooden grandstand was retained as left-field bleachers for a while, but was soon replaced with permanent bleachers.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The Cardinals came back to their original home in mid-1920, as tenants of the Browns, after abandoning the outdated and mostly-wooden Robison Field.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] After nearly winning the American League pennant in 1922, Browns owner Phil Ball confidently predicted that there would be a World Series in Sportsman's Park by 1926: in anticipation, he increased the capacity of his ballpark from 18,000 to 30,000.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] There *was* a World Series in Sportsman's Park in 1926—but it was the Cardinals, not the Browns, who took part in it, with the Cardinals upsetting the Yankees in a memorable seventh game.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Although the Browns had been the stronger team in the city for the first quarter of the century, they had never been quite good enough to win a pennant: after the previously weak Cardinals had moved in, the two teams' situations had started to reverse, both on and off the field.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The Cardinals' 1926 World Series victory more or less permanently tipped the balance in their favor, and from then on, the Cardinals were clearly St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis' favorite team, though still tenants of the Browns.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] In addition to its primary use as a baseball stadium, Sportsman's Park also hosted several soccer events.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis Soccer League, and the 1948 National Challenge Cup when St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis Simpkins-Ford defeated Brookhattan for the national soccer championship.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] His family sold the Browns to businessman Donald Lee Barnes, but the Ball estate maintained ownership of Sportsman's Park until 1946, when it was sold to the Browns for an estimated price of over US$1 million.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] By the early 1950s, it was clear that St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Bill Veeck, owner of the Browns (who at one point lived with his family in an apartment under the park's stands), fancied that he could drive the Cardinals out of town through his promotional skills.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] However, Veeck caught an unlucky break when the Cardinals' owner, Fred Saigh, pleaded no contest to tax evasion.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Faced with certain banishment from baseball, Saigh sold the Cardinals to Anheuser-Busch in February 1953.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Veeck soon realized that the Cardinals now had more resources at their disposal than he could ever hope to match.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Reluctantly, he concluded he was finished in St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis, and had no other option but to move the Browns.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] As a first step, he sold Sportsman's Park to the Cardinals for $800,000 on April 9.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Busch immediately renovated the stadium, which had not been well maintained in some time.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Even with the rent from the Cardinals, the Browns had not been bringing in nearly enough revenue to bring the park up to code, with city officials even threatening to have the park condemned.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Before the start of the next season, the Browns relocated to Baltimore and were rebranded as the Orioles.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The brewery originally wanted to name the ballpark Budweiser Stadium.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Commissioner Ford Frick vetoed the name because of public relations concerns over naming a ballpark after a brand of beer.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] However, the commissioner could not stop Anheuser-Busch president August Busch Jr. from renaming it after himself, so the park was renamed Busch Stadium.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] However, many fans still called it by the old name.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The Anheuser-Busch "eagle" model that sat atop the left field scoreboard flapped its wings after a Cardinal home run.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The next year, Anheuser-Busch introduced a new economy lager branded as "Busch Bavarian Beer", thus gaming Frick's ruling and allowing the ballpark's name to be branded by what would eventually be Anheuser-Busch's second most popular beer brand.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Sportsman's Park / Busch Stadium was the site of a number of World Series contests, first way back in the mid-1880s, and then in the modern era.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The 1964 Series was particularly memorable, the park's last, and featured brother against brother, Ken Boyer of the Cardinals and Clete Boyer of the Yankees.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The Cardinals' triumph in seven games led to Yankees management replacing Yogi Berra with the Cardinals' ex-manager Johnny Keane (he had resigned after winning the Series), an arrangement which lasted only to early 1966.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Louis natives, but neither had ever played for the Cardinals.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The stadium also hosted Major League Baseball All-Star Games in 1940, 1948, and 1957.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Despite Busch's extensive renovations, it soon became apparent that Sportsman's Park was at the end of its useful life.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Parking at the stadium was almost non-existent.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Its concrete-and-steel incarnation had been built only a year after the Model T was introduced, and had been designed in an era when fans took the trolley to games, making it ill-suited to automobile access.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Additionally, the neighborhood around the park had gone to seed; crime and dereliction has increased in the area as early as the late 1940s.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] In 1964, a Cardinals fan making his way to the home opener was shot and killed during an armed robbery.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Sportsman's Park/Busch Stadium was replaced early in the 1966 season by Busch Memorial Stadium, during which time much was made of baseball having been played on the old site for more than a century.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] A helicopter carried home plate to Busch Memorial Stadium after the final game at Sportsman's Park on May 8, 1966.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The 1966 stadium was replaced forty years later by the new Busch Stadium in April 2006.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] Donated by August Busch, the Sportsman's Park site became home to the Herbert Hoover Boys Club, which is now Boys & Girls Clubs of Greater St.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] While the grandstand was torn down in 1966, the diamond was still intact at the time the structures were cleared, and the field is now used for other sports.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] For a small park, there were plenty of posted distance markers.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The final major remodeling was done in 1926.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The following links provide images of the field's markers.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The diamond was conventionally aligned east-northeast (home plate to center field), and the elevation of the field was approximately 500 feet (150 m) above sea level.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The left field and right field walls ran toward center, roughly perpendicular to the foul lines or at right angles to each other.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The center field area was a short diagonal segment connecting the two longer walls.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] When distance markers were first posted, there was a 426 marker at the left corner of that segment, and a 422 marker at the right corner of it.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] There was another 422 marker a few feet to the left of the other one, and that marked "true" center field.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] For symmetry, a corresponding marker (425) was set a few feet to the right of the 426.
[src:sportsman-s-park/sportsman-s-park] The two corner markers were eventually painted over, leaving just the 425 and the true centerfield 422.
